    This is an example of a grazing incidence telescope.                      :
    It is used with nearly parallel incoming light -- often x-rays.           :
    The first reflection is from a concave paraboloid.                        :
    The second reflection is at a convex smaller paraboloid.                  :
    The outgoing light is again parallel, but concentrated.                   :
        :     :        :        :        :        :                           :
        :     :        :        :        :        :                           :
    Note the "<" in the tag column of the second mirror.                      :
    At grazing incidence, it is often necessary to specify                    :
    taking the shorter-ray-segment intercept, rather than the                 :
    usual default intercept closer to the vertex.  That is                    :
    what the "<" specifies.  Try removing it and see.                         :
